Can the euro be saved?
Paris — German Finance Minister Schäuble recently put the option of Greece exiting the euro on the table, hoping to send a signal that no member state is exempt from the strict discipline of the monetary union.
In fact, his proposal sparked a wide-ranging discussion about the principles underlying the euro, the euro governance model, and the rationale for the euro's existence.
Two weeks before Schäuble’s proposal was put forward, European leaders had already taken note of the report on the future of the euro written by Commission President Juncker and his colleagues from other EU institutions. However, the new debate over Greece has led many decision-makers to believe that returning to the original starting point is necessary.
Meanwhile, citizens are questioning why they should share a single currency?
Does this make sense? Can there be consensus on Greece's future?
Currency is like a nation; establishing it requires a myth.
Traditional wisdom holds that the euro was a political price Germany paid to France for re-unification.
In fact, German re-unification was merely the final step of an initiative that had taken shape in the 1980s to resolve a long-standing problem.
European governments strongly opposed floating exchange rates, believing they were incompatible with a single market; at the same time, they were unwilling to maintain a monetary system dominated by the German central bank for the long term.
A truly European currency based on German principles seemed to be the best solution.
In retrospect, German reunification was more of a curse than a blessing.
When exchange rates were fixed in 1999, Germany was overvalued and its economy was in difficulty; France was undervalued and its economy was thriving.
Over the following decade, imbalances gradually emerged between the resurgent Germany and countries experiencing credit booms due to low interest rates.
And with the outbreak of the 2008 global financial crisis, these conditions became the perfect storm.
No one knows what Europe would become without the euro.
Will the fixed exchange rate system continue or collapse?
Will the German mark remain overvalued?
Will countries reintroduce trade barriers and end the single market?
Will a real estate bubble emerge in Spain?
Will the government reform be more or less?
It is impossible to establish a reverse analysis baseline to evaluate the impact of the euro.
But this is by no means a reason for complacency.
Over the past 15 years, the eurozone economy has consistently delivered disappointing performance, and its political system must be held accountable for this.
What really matters is whether the common European currency will still be important for the future.
This issue is often avoided because the cost of exiting the euro is unimaginably high (and if the eurozone collapses during a crisis, and exacerbates mutual rivalry among member states, the costs would increase even further).
Moreover, abolishing the euro might unleash dark forces of nationalism and protectionism.
However, Kevin O’Rourke from the University of Oxford recently pointed out that this argument is not sufficient.
Logically, this is equivalent to suggesting that a couple should stay married because the cost of divorce is too high.
So, does the euro still make sense?
Originally, people expected the euro to bring three major economic benefits.
People assumed that the monetary union could promote economic integration and consolidate Europe's long-term growth.
On the contrary, internal trade and investment growth within the eurozone have been mediocre, and the growth potential has actually been weakened.
This is partly because national governments have not gone further than the monetary unification to build the eurozone into an economic superpower, but instead have tried to retain the power they still have.
This may be politically logical, but economically it is useless: Europe's vast internal market is one of its main assets, and therefore we must never waste the opportunity to strengthen the internal market.
Secondly, people hoped that the euro would become one of the major international currencies (especially considering that few countries meet the necessary legal, market, and policy frameworks).
According to the latest data from the European Central Bank, this hope has been largely realized.
The international use of the euro ranks second to the US dollar, an achievement that helps Europe continue to influence the global economic order rather than becoming an insignificant entity.
Thirdly, people (naively) believed that the institutions underlying the euro could improve the overall quality of economic policy, as if the European level of policy was inherently higher than the national level.
After the 2008 global financial crisis, a severe test came: the eurozone overemphasized the fiscal dimension of the crisis and underestimated its financial dimension, thus performing worse than the United States and the United Kingdom.
If the euro is to bring prosperity, it must further implement policy and institutional reforms.
But the formulation and implementation of a schedule must have a broad consensus on the nature of the problem.
The ongoing debates over Greece indicate that Europe is still far from reaching a consensus: participating countries have conflicting analyses of the roots of the debt crisis, leading to conflicting remedies.
Richard Cooper of Harvard University once observed that in the early stages of international public health cooperation, the governance of global diseases was greatly hindered by the different transmission patterns across countries.
Countries favor collective action, but cannot form a unified plan because they disagree on how diseases spread from one country to another.
This is the issue the eurozone faces today.
Fortunately, this issue is not unsolvable; major reforms such as the establishment of the European Stability Mechanism and the initiation of a banking union have demonstrated this.
Disagreements have not prevented the European Central Bank from taking decisive action, showing that institutional governance is indeed important.
But the fact that reforms and actions have only recently begun and were implemented under the pressure of serious crises makes people clearly aware of the difficulty in reaching consensus.
Europe can no longer delay or pretend.
The member states of the eurozone must establish a consistent agenda on governance and political reform to transform the monetary union into an engine of prosperity, otherwise they will only sink into repeated disputes and crises until citizens lose patience or markets lose trust.
Clarity is a prerequisite for serious discussion and major reforms.
Now, all major participants have an obligation to clearly define what they see as indispensable, what they find unacceptable, and what they are prepared to exchange for what they want.
